<div class="page-intro">
    <div class="eyebrow">A Bit About Me</div>
    <h1>Meet Lisa</h1>
    <p>
        Certified functional yoga therapist, mother, and soft-hearted guide for women
        navigating their most tender seasons.
    </p>
</div>

<section>
    <div class="container">
        <div class="about-block">
            <img
                src="/images/lisa.jpg"
                alt="Lisa Segar seated on a wood floor in front of a soft white wall, smiling warmly."
                class="about-image"
                loading="lazy"
                width="1600"
                height="1200"
            />
            <div>
                <p>
                    I've lived through many of the same transitions and emotional seasons my
                    clients face. I grew up navigating instability, abandonment, and big
                    feelings long before I knew how to care for myself. As a young woman, I
                    moved through relationships that echoed those early patterns—carrying
                    others' pain, losing pieces of myself, and trying to earn the love I
                    deserved.
                </p>
                <p>
                    My divorce and the sudden death of my ex-husband became a turning point.
                    Grief opened me in ways I didn't expect, revealing the strength and clarity
                    I'd been quietly building. Raising two incredible sons grounded me even
                    more—they reminded me that how I healed would shape how they grew. And in
                    time, finding love with a partner who sees, respects, and supports me
                    became part of that healing too. Being genuinely cared for showed me what
                    safety and reciprocity feel like.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="bg-sage">
    <div class="container narrow">
        <p>
            Yoga was integral in my healing. It helped me rewrite patterns I once thought were
            permanent. Yoga brought me back into my body after years of tension and
            hypervigilance. It softened old narratives and helped interrupt the loops of grief
            and trauma that felt hardwired. Through yoga I rebuilt my nervous system, my
            boundaries, and my relationship with myself.
        </p>
        <p>
            This is why I do the work I do. My lived experience—loss, transition, rebuilding,
            and finally cultivating the capacity to receive healthy love—allows me to sit with
            women in their own hard seasons without judgment. Through gentle movement, somatic
            practices, breathwork and mindfulness, I help women regulate their nervous systems,
            release long-held pain, and remember who they are beneath the survival patterns.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section>
    <div class="container narrow">
        <div class="pull-quote">
            "I'm not who I am in spite of my story—I'm who I am because of it. And I believe
            your healing can be just as steady, powerful, and soul-deep."
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

